<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the synthetic role assignment
    that grants the scoped role `x_[scope]_case_manager` to the synthetic demo
    user `x_[scope]_demo_manager`. This is one of exactly THREE role-assignment
    records in the case-management POC scoped application (the others grant
    the agent and viewer roles to their respective demo personas — see
    sys_user_has_role_x_[scope]_demo_agent.xml and
    sys_user_has_role_x_[scope]_demo_viewer.xml in this same directory).

    Persona role activated by this grant (per AAP Section 0.5.6 ACL Matrix):
      Once the Update Set commits, the demo manager user holds the
      x_[scope]_case_manager role and therefore receives:
        - x_[scope]_case        Create / Read All / Write All / Delete
        - x_[scope]_case_task   Create / Read All / Write All / Delete
        - x_[scope]_case_party  Create / Read All / Write All / Delete
      Unlike the case_agent persona, the manager's read/write scope is NOT
      restricted to "Assigned only" — the manager has unconditional full
      access on every row in the three custom tables regardless of
      assigned_agent / assigned_group, and is the only role permitted to
      Delete records on these tables. Per AAP Section 0.5.5 (State-Machine
      Transition Map), the manager is also the SOLE role authorized to
      perform the Resolved -> Closed transition; the
      validate_closed_transition subflow enforces this gate via
      gs.getUser().hasRole('x_[scope]_case_manager') and the role grant
      authored here is what makes the demo manager pass that check.

    Validation Gate 2 dependency (AAP Section 0.7.3):
      Per the Workflow gate's pass condition, all state transitions MUST
      be enforced for both case types — including the manager-only
      Resolved -> Closed transition. The demo cases at Resolved status
      (cases 05 General Inquiry, 09 Complaint per the seed data) cannot
      be moved to Closed during validation testing without a user holding
      the x_[scope]_case_manager role. This file is therefore the
      prerequisite that enables the operator to impersonate the demo
      manager and exercise the terminal Closed transition. Without THIS
      grant, no demo persona can close any case, and the Workflow gate's
      Resolved -> Closed scenario fails for both case types.

    Validation Gate 3 dependency (AAP Section 0.7.3):
      Per the ACL gate's pass condition "case_manager has full access",
      the operator impersonates the demo manager to verify create / read
      / write / delete privileges on all three custom scoped tables, and
      to verify write privileges on the field-level-protected fields
      assigned_group and assigned_agent (governed by
      ../../acl/x_[scope]_case_assigned_group_field_acl.xml and
      ../../acl/x_[scope]_case_assigned_agent_field_acl.xml). Without
      THIS role-assignment record, the demo manager holds no scoped role
      at all — making Gate 3's verification inconclusive (a denied write
      attempt could be due to no role grant rather than a properly
      enforced ACL pattern). This file is therefore central to Gate 3 of
      the seven-row validation framework.

    Why this assignment record lives in the SCOPED Update Set even though
    `sys_user_has_role` is a global OOB table:
      The scoped Update Set's deliverable is fully self-contained: the
      reviewer must be able to install the Update Set on a fresh PDI and
      immediately exercise all seven validation gates. The three demo
      personas (manager, agent, viewer) are required by Gate 2 (workflow
      transitions including the manager-only Resolved -> Closed), Gate 3
      (ACL role-based access), and Gate 6 (dashboard rendering with
      synthetic data — the Manager View dashboard is targeted at this
      persona). Tracking the role-assignment records inside the scoped
      Update Set ensures they import together with the rest of the
      application; the scope binding via <sys_scope> and <sys_package>
      source attribute groups them with the scoped app even though their
      parent table (sys_user_has_role) is global. No global-scope WRITES
      are performed: only INSERTS into sys_user_has_role (a data table) —
      the OOB sys_user_has_role dictionary, ACLs, and form layouts are
      never modified.

    Authoring rules honored (per AAP Sections 0.7.1 / 0.7.2 and the agent
    prompt's eight authoring rules):

      Rule 1 — Synthetic Only:
        <user> resolves to `x_[scope]_demo_manager` — a fully synthetic
        demo persona created by ../users/sys_user_x_[scope]_demo_manager.xml
        with the unmistakably non-real first_name "Demo" and last_name
        "Manager" and the synthetic email demo-manager@example.invalid
        (RFC 2606 reserved-TLD). <role> resolves to `x_[scope]_case_manager`
        — a brand-new scoped role defined by
        ../../roles/sys_user_role_x_[scope]_case_manager.xml. Both sides
        of this association are unmistakably non-real and live exclusively
        inside the x_[scope] scope. NO real users (no admin, no system)
        and NO OOB roles (no itil, no snc_internal, no
        personalize_dictionary, no admin) are referenced.

      Rule 2 — Zero Hardcoded sys_id Cross-References:
        - The record's OWN <sys_id> below is THIS record's identity key
          (acceptable per AAP rule). It is a deterministic 32-character
          lowercase hex value (MD5 of the canonical
          "x_[scope]_demo_manager:x_[scope]_case_manager" tuple) so the
          Update Set engine resolves the same sys_id on every PDI,
          guaranteeing idempotent re-imports during round-trip
          verification. The same MD5-of-tuple algorithm is used by the
          sibling sys_user_has_role_x_[scope]_demo_viewer.xml record for
          consistency.
        - The <user> reference resolves by display_value="x_[scope]_demo_manager"
          — the Update Set engine looks up sys_user.user_name = "x_[scope]_demo_manager"
          at apply time. The text-node value is the same lookup key (NOT
          a hardcoded sys_id literal) per the project convention used by
          every ACL <roles> field (e.g., ../../acl/x_[scope]_case_read_manager.xml
          uses <roles>x_[scope]_case_manager</roles> as a name lookup,
          not a sys_id literal).
        - The <role> reference resolves by display_value="x_[scope]_case_manager"
          — the Update Set engine looks up sys_user_role.name = "x_[scope]_case_manager"
          at apply time. The text-node value is the same lookup key.
        - The <sys_scope> and <sys_package> fields resolve by
          display_value / source attribute lookup against the scoped
          application's sys_scope record (../../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml,
          where <source>x_[scope]</source>). The text-node value
          "x_[scope]" is the scope's source key — the canonical project
          convention used by every other scoped artifact in the Update
          Set, including the sibling demo viewer role-assignment record.

      Rule 3 — Scope Binding:
        <sys_scope> binds this assignment record to the scoped application
        whose source attribute is "x_[scope]" (defined in
        ../../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml). The display_value attribute
        is "Case Management" — the human-readable scoped-app name. The
        <sys_package> follows the same pattern with the source attribute
        pointing at the scope source name. Although sys_user_has_role is
        a global OOB table, the SCOPED demo grant is tracked in the
        scoped Update Set so the deliverable is fully self-contained.

      Rule 4 — No Inheritance:
        <inherited>false</inherited> (literal lowercase string "false").
        Group-based role inheritance is NOT used in this POC; this is a
        direct user-to-role grant. If <inherited>true</inherited> were
        used, the platform would interpret this row as derivative of a
        parent group's role grant, which would be inconsistent with the
        canonical pattern. Critically, the demo manager is intentionally
        NOT a member of x_[scope]_demo_team (only the demo agent is a
        member — see ../groups/sys_user_group_x_[scope]_demo_team.xml),
        so even if group-level role inheritance were permitted, the
        manager would not inherit anything from the group. The manager's
        full-access privilege is encoded entirely at the table-level ACL
        via this direct grant — no group membership is required, keeping
        the manager's privilege surface unconditional per AAP Section
        0.5.6.

      Rule 5 — Active State:
        <state>active</state> (literal lowercase string "active"). The
        role assignment is effective immediately upon Update Set commit.
        Inactive states (requested, pending, expired) are workflow-
        related and not used in the POC seeding flow.

      Rule 6 — Idempotency Anchor:
        The record's idempotent key is the (user, role) tuple
        ("x_[scope]_demo_manager", "x_[scope]_case_manager"). The
        companion seed script ../../scripts/seed_demo_data.js's
        ensureRoleAssignment(DEMO.USERS.MANAGER, ROLES.MANAGER) helper
        queries by both fields BEFORE inserting; the
        action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE" attribute on the inner
        <sys_user_has_role> element provides the equivalent idempotency
        guarantee at Update Set commit time. These exact display_value
        strings MUST match the corresponding values in
        ../users/sys_user_x_[scope]_demo_manager.xml (<user_name> =
        "x_[scope]_demo_manager") and
        ../../roles/sys_user_role_x_[scope]_case_manager.xml (<name> =
        "x_[scope]_case_manager") — verified at authoring time.

      Rule 7 — Minimum Field Set:
        ONLY the four content fields required by the agent prompt's
        Mandatory Field Specification are populated: user, role,
        inherited, state. Plus the standard ServiceNow housekeeping
        (sys_class_name, sys_id, sys_scope, sys_package, sys_created_by,
        sys_update_name). All additional sys_user_has_role columns
        (granted_by, u_*, etc.) are auto-defaulted by the platform on
        first import. This keeps the file small, avoids dependencies on
        other global tables (no granted_by reference to another sys_user),
        and makes the record resilient to ServiceNow release-version
        drift across Yokohama / Zurich / Australia.

      Rule 8 — Scoped Update Set XML Conventions:
        Root element: <record_update table="sys_user_has_role">
        Inner element: <sys_user_has_role action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        for idempotent re-import per AAP Section 0.7.1 round-trip-
        verification.
        UTF-8 encoding declared in XML prolog.
        Boolean values lowercase: <inherited>false</inherited>.
        Element ordering: alphabetical (matching the sibling
        sys_user_has_role_x_[scope]_demo_viewer.xml record and every
        other XML in the scoped Update Set).

    Cross-dependencies (per AAP Section 0.5.2):

      This grant DEPENDS ON (must be loaded BEFORE this record):
        - ../../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml (scoped app)
        - ../../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml (scope record - resolves
          sys_scope and sys_package source="x_[scope]")
        - ../users/sys_user_x_[scope]_demo_manager.xml (the demo manager
          user — resolves <user> by user_name lookup)
        - ../../roles/sys_user_role_x_[scope]_case_manager.xml (the
          scoped role — resolves <role> by name lookup)

      Records that DEPEND ON this grant (loaded AFTER this record):
        - The 4 manager-targeted ACL records at
          ../../acl/x_[scope]_case_create_manager.xml,
          ../../acl/x_[scope]_case_read_manager.xml,
          ../../acl/x_[scope]_case_write_manager.xml,
          ../../acl/x_[scope]_case_delete_manager.xml (plus the mirror
          ACL records for x_[scope]_case_task and x_[scope]_case_party)
          — the manager's full CRUD privileges on all three scoped
          tables are encoded in these ACLs and are activated for the
          demo manager via this grant.
        - The 2 field-level ACL records at
          ../../acl/x_[scope]_case_assigned_group_field_acl.xml and
          ../../acl/x_[scope]_case_assigned_agent_field_acl.xml — write
          access to these sensitive assignment fields is restricted to
          the case_manager role (and partially to the assigned
          case_agent for the assigned_agent field). Without this grant,
          the demo manager could not modify either field on any case.
        - The validate_closed_transition subflow at
          ../../flows/sub_flows/validate_closed_transition.xml — gates
          the Resolved -> Closed transition behind
          gs.getUser().hasRole('x_[scope]_case_manager'); without this
          grant, the demo manager fails the role check and the demo
          cases stuck at Resolved (cases 05, 09 per the seed data)
          cannot be transitioned to Closed during validation testing.
        - The set_closed_date business rule at
          ../../business_rules/x_[scope]_set_closed_date.xml — auto-sets
          closed_date = gs.nowDateTime() when the manager-driven
          Resolved -> Closed transition is permitted by the subflow
          above; this grant is the upstream prerequisite that allows
          the BR to fire.
        - Validation Gate 2 (Workflow) testing — the operator
          impersonates the demo manager to verify the manager-only
          Resolved -> Closed transition succeeds for both case types
          (General Inquiry on case 05, Complaint on case 09).
        - Validation Gate 3 (ACLs) testing — the operator impersonates
          the demo manager to verify full CRUD on all three scoped
          tables.
        - Person-type demo party records at
          ../parties/x_[scope]_case_party_demo_*.xml — some parties use
          the demo manager as the `person` reference (per the seed-
          script's party table: case 03 Requester party, case 08
          Requester party). Although the person reference resolves
          regardless of role grants, validation tests will involve
          impersonating the manager to read/write these parties.

    Source-side semantic reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported)
    per AAP Sections 0.8.1 and 0.7.1:
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/
        services/users/model/ApplicationRolesConfig.java
        Holds `application.roles` as List<String> bound from external
        configuration via @ListValue("application.roles") and exposes
        MERGE_APPLICATION_ROLES_OP = "application.~roles". Semantic
        reference for ArkCase's role-list configuration model. ArkCase's
        mechanism (config-driven `application.roles` list bound to user
        -> role mappings via RolesPrivilegesService) is replaced in the
        target by this OOB ServiceNow sys_user_has_role join-table row
        authored fresh — there is no field-by-field mapping from
        ArkCase's Java model to sys_user_has_role.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-admin-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/admin/service/RolesPrivilegesService.java
        Central CRUD / normalization service for ArkCase role / privilege
        management. ArkCase normalizes role names by uppercasing,
        replacing whitespace with underscores, replacing periods with
        double-underscores, and prepending ROLE_PREFIX = "ROLE_". The
        ServiceNow target replaces this normalization with the scope-
        prefix convention (x_[scope]_); the ROLE_ prefix is intentionally
        NOT used. Per AAP Section 0.7.1 ("API-compatibility preservation
        is explicitly NOT required"), the ArkCase role-assignment
        infrastructure (Spring service classes, REST controllers under
        /api/v1/plugin/admin/... and /api/latest/plugin/admin/...) is
        explicitly NOT replicated.

    Validation hooks (per the agent prompt):
      - XML well-formedness check using xmllint in its no-output mode
        returns zero errors.
      - The standard no-PII grep targeting common consumer first-name
        and surname patterns plus consumer-email-domain TLD patterns
        returns zero matches in the actual data fields of this record;
        the synthetic identifiers used here (the demo persona user_name
        and the scoped role name) do not include any PII tokens.
      - The standard no-extra-fields grep targeting the granted_by
        element name and the custom-prefix element name pattern returns
        zero matches; neither the granted_by element nor any custom-
        prefixed element is populated on this record.
      - Cross-reference resolution: the display_value="x_[scope]_demo_manager"
        value matches the <user_name>x_[scope]_demo_manager</user_name>
        value in ../users/sys_user_x_[scope]_demo_manager.xml exactly;
        the display_value="x_[scope]_case_manager" value matches the
        <name>x_[scope]_case_manager</name> value in
        ../../roles/sys_user_role_x_[scope]_case_manager.xml exactly.
      - The literal `[scope]` placeholder is preserved verbatim per AAP
        convention; the PDI auto-assigns the actual concrete scope id
        at App Engine Studio creation time, and the Update-Set apply-
        time substitution propagates consistently across all bracketed
        placeholders in this artifact.
-->
<record_update table="sys_user_has_role">
    <sys_user_has_role action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <inherited>false</inherited>
        <role display_value="x_[scope]_case_manager">x_[scope]_case_manager</role>
        <state>active</state>
        <sys_class_name>sys_user_has_role</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_id>c6ed64934879ee3ea435a2276bb5bf79</sys_id>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]">x_[scope]</sys_package>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_user_has_role_x_[scope]_demo_manager</sys_update_name>
        <user display_value="x_[scope]_demo_manager">x_[scope]_demo_manager</user>
    </sys_user_has_role>
</record_update>
